1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,480
Data modeling is one of the most important skills that data engineers have to learn.

2
00:00:03,720 --> 00:00:05,660
So how is it so important?

3
00:00:05,900 --> 00:00:11,080
Well, at the end of the day, data modeling is the structure of the data that we create

4
00:00:11,080 --> 00:00:15,900
for businesses because the asset that we produce for businesses is data to make better decisions.

5
00:00:16,240 --> 00:00:18,900
And data modeling has a bunch of different components to it.

6
00:00:18,960 --> 00:00:20,220
And we're going to talk about each of them.

7
00:00:20,360 --> 00:00:22,980
There's the highest level, it's called conceptual data modeling.

8
00:00:23,120 --> 00:00:26,720
Then we're going to be going over the next layer down, which is logical data modeling.

9
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:30,180
And then the final layer that we're going to talk about is physical data modeling.

10
00:00:30,320 --> 00:00:31,980
In this video, we should be covering all of those.

11
00:00:32,120 --> 00:00:35,480
So at the end of this, you should know all the ins and outs of all three types of these

12
00:00:35,480 --> 00:00:35,920
data modeling.

13
00:00:36,140 --> 00:00:40,860
So let's first talk about the highest level conceptual data modeling, which is the highest

14
00:00:40,860 --> 00:00:43,820
level way of thinking about it is like, what data do we need?

15
00:00:44,040 --> 00:00:46,120
What data does the business desire?

16
00:00:46,300 --> 00:00:48,140
What data do we have access to?

17
00:00:48,280 --> 00:00:49,200
What are the sources?

18
00:00:49,560 --> 00:00:50,840
Where can we find this data?

19
00:00:51,100 --> 00:00:55,020
Can we like think about all the relationships of this data, like at a very high level?

20
00:00:55,020 --> 00:01:00,780
because sometimes you might want data in a business, but it's actually unfeasible to get it,

21
00:01:00,820 --> 00:01:04,120
or it's going to take months and months and months, and it's not ROI positive,

22
00:01:04,120 --> 00:01:08,060
because the time it would take to get the data is more than the value you can get out of it.

23
00:01:08,240 --> 00:01:13,960
So this area of data modeling is very, very, very important, because if you get this wrong,

24
00:01:14,140 --> 00:01:19,440
you can end up spending a lot of extra time on the data model for things that don't matter that much.

25
00:01:19,560 --> 00:01:24,620
Like there might be an extra column or an extra table that like some data scientists ask for

26
00:01:24,620 --> 00:01:29,540
that they're only going to use one time. And if you push back on that, it makes your job as a data

27
00:01:29,540 --> 00:01:34,180
engineer a lot easier because you remove that requirement because it's a low value requirement.

28
00:01:34,360 --> 00:01:38,340
So you need to be able to like walk through all the requirements of the data model at this highest

29
00:01:38,340 --> 00:01:44,960
level. And really having a deep understanding of the business is where you can really, really shine

30
00:01:44,960 --> 00:01:50,640
as a data engineer with conceptual data modeling. So after you have mastered the conceptual data

31
00:01:50,640 --> 00:01:54,760
model, you skip into the next layer, which is the logical data model.

32
00:01:54,780 --> 00:02:07,885
So the logical data model is where you start talking about like facts and dimensions and how they related Like so facts are events You can think of that as like I click the login button I purchase a product I

33
00:02:07,885 --> 00:02:12,645
send a message to a friend. Like all of these are like events and actions that you can take on a

34
00:02:12,645 --> 00:02:17,225
website. And these are going to be your facts because they can't really change. After I've

35
00:02:17,225 --> 00:02:23,065
logged in on Facebook at 6.03 p.m. like I can't go back into a time machine and change that. So

36
00:02:23,065 --> 00:02:28,165
then you have dimensions, which are going to be like your nouns or like your actors in this space,

37
00:02:28,245 --> 00:02:34,665
right? So you have things like users or listings or posts or, you know, devices. These are all

38
00:02:34,665 --> 00:02:40,385
like things that bring context because like I could be like, I'm a user in China who clicks

39
00:02:40,385 --> 00:02:46,085
an ad, right? And then the user in China bit, that part of my user object, and then clicking the ad

40
00:02:46,085 --> 00:02:50,745
is part of the fact. And so those are the ways to be thinking about all of these things. So the

41
00:02:50,745 --> 00:02:57,025
logical data model is all about how do you find all of these entities and how are they related.

42
00:02:57,205 --> 00:03:01,905
So like, for example, when you click on an ad on Facebook, the entities that are involved,

43
00:03:02,005 --> 00:03:06,105
the user who clicked the ad, you also have the device that clicked the ad. You also have the

44
00:03:06,105 --> 00:03:11,085
browser potentially that clicked the ad. And so those are three dimensions that you can bring

45
00:03:11,085 --> 00:03:18,785
in to your fact data to make your fact data richer and more powerful. So after you have gotten the

46
00:03:18,785 --> 00:03:25,585
logical data layer nailed down then you move into the final layer which is the physical layer and

47
00:03:25,585 --> 00:03:30,885
this is the layer where people oftentimes like they think the physical layer is the only part

48
00:03:30,885 --> 00:03:35,285
of data modeling when it's actually not it's actually like probably the least important in

49
00:03:35,285 --> 00:03:39,665
some in some regards but it's also where it becomes real it becomes reality it's physical

50
00:03:39,665 --> 00:03:44,125
data now so this is where you start looking at the schema what are the columns of your data like

51
00:03:44,125 --> 00:03:48,465
what are the data types of your data how are you storing this data how can you compress this data

52
00:03:48,465 --> 00:03:49,325
to make it smaller.

53
00:03:49,325 --> 00:03:50,425
So in this space,

54
00:03:50,425 --> 00:03:51,565
you have a couple of different

55
00:03:51,565 --> 00:03:52,965
data modeling techniques

56
00:03:52,965 --> 00:03:54,105
that you can look into

57
00:03:54,105 --> 00:03:55,065
that can really help

58
00:03:55,065 --> 00:03:56,465
understand all the way up

59
00:03:56,465 --> 00:04:07,750
from like physical to logical to conceptual And you can like understand there a couple different paradigms here So one is called one big table So one big table essentially says you don need facts and

60
00:04:07,750 --> 00:04:12,970
dimensions. You can essentially have a fact that has all of its context. All of the context is

61
00:04:12,970 --> 00:04:16,690
already in the fact. So you don't need to do joins. You can just do aggregations. You don't

62
00:04:16,690 --> 00:04:22,111
need to join at all because when data gets very big, joins become very expensive, like actually

63
00:04:22,111 --> 00:04:28,130
joining in the nouns into your data. But the trade here, right, is that you're duplicating data,

64
00:04:28,291 --> 00:04:34,811
right? Because every now my user data is now in every single fact, right? And say I do 300 events

65
00:04:34,811 --> 00:04:40,950
on a data set. This is what's called the compute storage trade-off, right? Because it is duplicated

66
00:04:40,950 --> 00:04:47,570
in storage. But why is this potentially worth it? It's because you can now do aggregations without

67
00:04:47,570 --> 00:04:52,291
doing join and aggregations are faster than join because you don't have to like pull data from all

68
00:04:52,291 --> 00:04:56,750
these different locations you can just aggregate right down and group very quickly and so this is

69
00:04:56,750 --> 00:05:02,330
what is the advantage of one big table even though one big table also duplicates a lot of data and is

70
00:05:02,330 --> 00:05:07,151
super painful so then you have the more traditional approach of facts and dimensions where like you

71
00:05:07,151 --> 00:05:11,930
separate your nouns and you separate your verbs and your events and then you join them together

72
00:05:11,930 --> 00:05:16,651
that's called dimensional data modeling dimensional data modeling is the oldest technique of all the

73
00:05:16,651 --> 00:05:20,690
techniques that we have talked about, and it's the one that most data engineers should probably pick.

74
00:05:20,791 --> 00:05:24,971
It's the most foundational and the most fundamental. So definitely, if you haven't learned about

75
00:05:24,971 --> 00:05:30,130
dimensional data modeling, I'll put a link in the description below. I have many hours of content on

76
00:05:30,130 --> 00:05:33,911
dimensional data modeling on my YouTube channel. And then last but not least here is called a data

77
00:05:33,911 --> 00:05:39,591
vault. So data vault is very interesting because data vault is all about preserving the rawness of

78
00:05:39,591 --> 00:05:44,750
the data. So you want to bring in data in its most untransformed state and kind of stack it onto

79
00:05:44,750 --> 00:05:49,750
of things, and this allows you to essentially know exactly what the data was in its rawest form.

80
00:05:49,750 --> 00:05:54,791
So you don't end up filtering something out that you didn't mean to or transform something that you made a mistake on.

81
00:05:54,791 --> 00:06:13,296
And Data Vault allows you to back up into like the most raw form of the data It kind of related to ELT you know extract load transform instead of extract transform load That it kind of related to that But it also about how you actually model the data And it has a very strict kind of thing in it and like a strict kind of ideology to it That why

82
00:06:13,296 --> 00:06:16,916
I don't really I don't really subscribe to data vault as much. I really like dimensional data

83
00:06:16,916 --> 00:06:21,656
modeling and one big table data modeling. But at the end of the day, like it's still a very useful

84
00:06:21,656 --> 00:06:25,636
technique and you can combine all of these techniques. I'm going to give an example. So

85
00:06:25,636 --> 00:06:32,376
when I worked at Airbnb, I actually built a data model that was a mix of one big table and data

86
00:06:32,376 --> 00:06:37,416
vault and dimensional data modeling. So how it worked was we use data vault to get all of the

87
00:06:37,416 --> 00:06:43,136
inputs. So the inputs in this case were for availability and price because the host sets

88
00:06:43,136 --> 00:06:48,736
the price rules. Like what is the daily price? Are there any discounts? Are there any like any

89
00:06:48,736 --> 00:06:52,576
length of stay requirements? Maybe you have to book for three days or seven days, or, you know,

90
00:06:52,576 --> 00:06:54,476
you can only book 48 hours in advance.

91
00:06:54,476 --> 00:06:57,416
There's a lot of these different rules that hosts can set in Airbnb.

92
00:06:57,436 --> 00:07:00,736
And so I took all those rules in their raw form and combine them

93
00:07:00,736 --> 00:07:02,516
into one dataset called inputs.

94
00:07:02,536 --> 00:07:05,276
And that was the data vault kind of technique that I used.

95
00:07:05,276 --> 00:07:08,996
And then from the inputs table, we process it through to a

96
00:07:08,996 --> 00:07:11,096
new table called listing pricing.

97
00:07:11,116 --> 00:07:14,596
So now we actually know what the actual prices would have been given those rules.

98
00:07:14,636 --> 00:07:20,356
And that table was one big table because it had all of the nights in one column.

99
00:07:20,356 --> 00:07:26,116
So one of the giveaways of like a one big table data set is that it uses complex data types.

100
00:07:26,116 --> 00:07:34,976
Like it uses things like struct and array and like map and those kind of like more complicated data types more than just like, you know, string and integer and decimal.

101
00:07:35,176 --> 00:07:38,336
It's like one big table very often is a table within a table.

102
00:07:38,576 --> 00:07:40,576
And that was a big thing I did here at Airbnb.

103
00:07:40,756 --> 00:07:48,036
Keeping in mind that like you don't have to adhere to any one of these three religions when you are working with data modeling.

104
00:07:48,036 --> 00:07:50,456
you can also kind of do whatever you want, right?

105
00:07:50,576 --> 00:07:51,656
And mix and match.

106
00:07:51,796 --> 00:07:53,356
It's more of an art than a science.

